{"repo": "eliben/pyelftools", "pull_number": 628, "instance_id": "eliben__pyelftools-628", "issue_numbers": [612], "base_commit": "3b2d8c40e06d58372a2f27686fac953dfb9f7e05", "patch": "diff --git a/elftools/elf/descriptions.py b/elftools/elf/descriptions.py\nindex a86027f2..69422c17 100644\n--- a/elftools/elf/descriptions.py\n+++ b/elftools/elf/descriptions.py\n@@ -27,7 +27,7 @@ def describe_ei_data(x):\n \n \n def describe_ei_version(x):\n-    s = '%d' % ENUM_E_VERSION[x]\n+    s = str(ENUM_E_VERSION.get(x, f\"{x} <unknown>\"))\n     if x == 'EV_CURRENT':\n         s += ' (current)'\n     return s\n@@ -41,9 +41,10 @@ def describe_e_type(x, elffile=None):\n     if elffile is not None and x == 'ET_DYN':\n         # Detect whether this is a normal SO or a PIE executable\n         dynamic = elffile.get_section_by_name('.dynamic')\n-        for t in dynamic.iter_tags('DT_FLAGS_1'):\n-            if t.entry.d_val & ENUM_DT_FLAGS_1['DF_1_PIE']:\n-                return 'DYN (Position-Independent Executable file)'\n+        if dynamic:\n+            for t in dynamic.iter_tags('DT_FLAGS_1'):\n+                if t.entry.d_val & ENUM_DT_FLAGS_1['DF_1_PIE']:\n+                    return 'DYN (Position-Independent Executable file)'\n     return _DESCR_E_TYPE.get(x, _unknown)\n \n \n@@ -52,7 +53,7 @@ def describe_e_machine(x):\n \n \n def describe_e_version_numeric(x):\n-    return '0x%x' % ENUM_E_VERSION[x]\n+    return f\"{ENUM_E_VERSION.get(x, x):#x}\"\n \n \n def describe_p_type(x):\ndiff --git a/elftools/elf/elffile.py b/elftools/elf/elffile.py\nindex 6efc27ca..a5953814 100644\n--- a/elftools/elf/elffile.py\n+++ b/elftools/elf/elffile.py\n@@ -84,8 +84,7 @@ def __init__(self, stream, stream_loader=None):\n         self.stream.seek(0)\n         self.e_ident_raw = self.stream.read(16)\n \n-        self._section_header_stringtable = \\\n-            self._get_section_header_stringtable()\n+        self._section_header_stringtable = None # Lazy load\n         self._section_name_map = None\n         self.stream_loader = stream_loader\n \n@@ -693,8 +692,10 @@ def _get_section_name(self, section_header):\n         \"\"\" Given a section header, find this section's name in the file's\n             string table\n         \"\"\"\n-        if self._section_header_stringtable is None:\n-            raise ELFParseError(\"String Table not found\")\n+        if self._section_header_stringtable is None: # Try to lazy load\n+            self._section_header_stringtable = self._get_section_header_stringtable()\n+            if self._section_header_stringtable is None: # If absent (or badly malformed)\n+                raise ELFParseError(\"String Table not found\")\n \n         name_offset = section_header['sh_name']\n         return self._section_header_stringtable.get_string(name_offset)\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Uncaught exceptions on fuzzed but valid ELF files\nI've read previous, similar issues about fuzzing #529  and corrupted ELF files #482. I've followed the rule of thumb as laid out by sevaa there\n\n> In general, our preferred rule of thumb is - can the GNU or the LLVM tools (e. g. readelf) parse the binary with no errors? If they do, and pyelftools throws an error, it's issue with pyelftools. Else, it's the issue with the binary.\n\nWell, using the fuzzer Atheris I found 19 uncaught exceptions. I've logged all offending ELF files, and only logged them if `llvm-readelf` returned without exit. \n\nTo be precise, I made this check as such: \n\n```Python\n            result = subprocess.run(['llvm-readelf', '--addrsig', '--arch-specific', '--bb-addr-map', '--demangle', '--dependent-libraries', '--dyn-relocations', '--dyn-symbols', '--dynamic-table', '--cg-profile', '--histogram', '--elf-linker-options', '--section-groups', '--expand-relocs', '--file-header', '--gnu-hash-table', '--hash-symbols', '--elf-output-style=JSON', '--pretty-print', '--hash-table', '--headers', '--needed-libs', '--notes', '--program-headers', '--relocations', '--sections', '--section-data', '--section-mapping', '--section-relocations', '--section-symbols', '--stackmap', '--stack-sizes', '--symbols', '--unwind', '--version-info', temp_file_path], capture_output=True, text=False)\n            if result.returncode == 0:\n                # Log the crash only if llvm-readelf succeeded\n                log_crash(e, data, CRASH_DIR)\n            else:\n                pass\n                # print(f\"llvm-readelf failed to parse the file: {temp_file_path}\")\n```\n\nI tried to make `llvm-parse` parse as much as possible of the ELF file this way, to make the comparison as fair as possible. \n\nI logged the crashing ELF files, as well as a JSON containing more information (such as the stack trace), for example: \n\n```JSON\n{\n    \"exception_type\": \"<class 'UnicodeDecodeError'>\",\n    \"exception_message\": \"'utf-8' codec can't decode byte 0xff in position 4: invalid start byte\",\n    \"traceback\": \"Traceback (most recent call last):\\n  File \\\"/root/pyelftools/fuzzing.py\\\", line 111, in TestOneInput\\n    readelf.main()\\n  File \\\"/root/pyelftools/scripts/readelf.py\\\", line 1955, in main\\n    readelf.display_arch_specific()\\n  File \\\"/root/pyelftools/scripts/readelf.py\\\", line 800, in display_arch_specific\\n    self._display_arch_specific_arm()\\n  File \\\"/root/pyelftools/scripts/readelf.py\\\", line 1830, in _display_arch_specific_arm\\n    self._display_attributes(attr_sec, describe_attr_tag_arm)\\n  File \\\"/root/pyelftools/scripts/readelf.py\\\", line 1821, in _display_attributes\\n    for attr in ss.iter_attributes():\\n  File \\\"/root/pyelftools/elftools/elf/sections.py\\\", line 335, in iter_attributes\\n    for attribute in self._make_attributes():\\n  File \\\"/root/pyelftools/elftools/elf/sections.py\\\", line 360, in _make_attributes\\n    yield self.attribute(self.structs, self.stream)\\n          ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\\n  File \\\"/root/pyelftools/elftools/elf/sections.py\\\", line 495, in __init__\\n    self.value = struct_parse(structs.Elf_ntbs('value',\\n                 ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\\n  File \\\"/root/pyelftools/elftools/common/utils.py\\\", line 36, in struct_parse\\n    return struct.parse_stream(stream)\\n           ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\\n  File \\\"/root/pyelftools/elftools/construct/core.py\\\", line 190, in parse_stream\\n    return self._parse(stream, Container())\\n           ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\\n  File \\\"/root/pyelftools/elftools/construct/core.py\\\", line 261, in _parse\\n    return self.subcon._parse(stream, context)\\n           ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\\n  File \\\"/root/pyelftools/elftools/construct/core.py\\\", line 276, in _parse\\n    return self._decode(self.subcon._parse(stream, context), context)\\n           ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\\n  File \\\"/root/pyelftools/elftools/construct/adapters.py\\\", line 238, in _decode\\n    return StringAdapter._decode(self, b''.join(obj[:-1]), context)\\n           ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\\n  File \\\"/root/pyelftools/elftools/construct/adapters.py\\\", line 153, in _decode\\n    obj = obj.decode(self.encoding)\\n          ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\\nUnicodeDecodeError: 'utf-8' codec can't decode byte 0xff in position 4: invalid start byte\\n\",\n    \"input_data\": \"\",\n    \"crashing_file_path\": \"elftools/construct/adapters.py\"\n}\n```\n\nNow I wonder, given that `llvm-parseelf` seems to parse them with no error, are you interested in further investigating these crashes?  If so, how can I best provide them to you in a way that you find convenient?\n\nI don't mean to simply drop the dirty work on you here. I've looked into the crashes but I lack thorough understanding of the ELF format to make a well-informed decision. I hope that comparing with `llvm-readelf` makes sense, if you'd like me to do any other comparison before storing them as a crash, let me know! Also, if you're interested in this fuzzing setup, I\u00b4d be happy to help you set it up. \n", "hints_text": "I'd take a closer look. Is it the the same exception on 19 binaries, or 19 exceptions in different places?\n\nI can think of some cases, though, when an ELF file is malformed in a nonfatal way, so that readelf can recover and continue without something as drastic as quitting with an error code. Here and there in the format, you see small, self contained chunks with known length and known format. GNU notes and ARM/RISC-V attributes come to mind. If one of those is malformed or otherwise unparseable, readelf-like tools would give you an unparsed hex dump and keep going, and that's the correct behavior. One may say that for a parser library that is not the topmost layer in the stack, such as pyelftools, throwing an exception on one of those _is also the correct behavior_, and recovery/fallback should be handled by the caller.\n\nNotably, the provided traceback is about a note.\n\nI don't think we should strive to match the behavior of GNU readelf or llvm-readelf when it comes to those nonfatal parse errors. That's not the purpose of readelf.py.\n@bakeromso\n\n> are you interested in further investigating these crashes? \n\nYes.\n\n> If so, how can I best provide them to you in a way that you find convenient?\n\nLet's start by providing one faulty binary, as an attachment to a comment on this very issue, zipped up (as GitHub won't let you provide a raw binary). I'll see where it takes us.\n@bakeromso \n\nIs this still an issue?\n@sevaa yes it is but I've not yet come around to recreating the test setup\n@sevaa sorry about the delay. Here is a zip with the ELFs that give a crash with pyelftools, but no crash with llvm-readelf.\n\nI get the crash by running `readelf.py -h [name of elf file].elf`\n\n[crashes.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/22929255/crashes.zip)\n### col_12to35_line35to35_ValueError.elf\nBogus stringtable section offset; pyelftools tries to retrieve its header eagerly and crashes. Lazy retrieval logic is already in place, this can be fixed trivially. **Modulo that**, the `e_version` in the ELF header is bogus (0xFFFFFFF) and is not in the enum - again, trivial fix - check if the value is in the enum before looking up.\n\n### col_15to32_line30to30_KeyError.elf\nBogus `EI_VERSION` in the header, one not in the enum - fix along the same lines.\n\n### col_17to34_line44to44_AttributeError.elf\nType ET_DYN, but no section called .dynamic. Trivial fix - check before dump. \n\n### col_20to37_line55to55_KeyError.elf\nBogus `e_version` again.\n\nIn conclusion, the mismatches *in header dump* can be addressed fairly easily, but other than satisfying one's obsession with matching llvm-readelf bug tolerance for bug tolerance, I don't see a ton of value there. Maybe some degree of vague future proofing, were those enums to legitimately become extended (which is quite unlikely). Also some limited value to those among us who study corrupt files for fun and/or living.\n\nNote that readelf dumps more involved than -h (dump file header) don't work in GNU readelf either; on as much as -S (section header dump) on 3 out of 4 files GNU readelf claims the file has no sections. I suspect the section header table is damaged on all of them but the only damage that pyelftools would surface is the corrupt stringtable.\nThank you for the follow up. Feel free to close the issue if this isn't worth the effort of fixing like you said, I understand.\n@eliben\n\nIt's a small set of fixes that will impose no performance penalty on the library proper. What do you think?\n> [@eliben](https://github.com/eliben)\n> \n> It's a small set of fixes that will impose no performance penalty on the library proper. What do you think?\n\nIf it's pretty minimal - just like a few safety checks here and there, I'm OK with merging it. Happy to take a look at a PR for specifics\n\nThanks!\n\n", "all_hints_text": "I'd take a closer look. Is it the the same exception on 19 binaries, or 19 exceptions in different places?\n\nI can think of some cases, though, when an ELF file is malformed in a nonfatal way, so that readelf can recover and continue without something as drastic as quitting with an error code. Here and there in the format, you see small, self contained chunks with known length and known format. GNU notes and ARM/RISC-V attributes come to mind. If one of those is malformed or otherwise unparseable, readelf-like tools would give you an unparsed hex dump and keep going, and that's the correct behavior. One may say that for a parser library that is not the topmost layer in the stack, such as pyelftools, throwing an exception on one of those _is also the correct behavior_, and recovery/fallback should be handled by the caller.\n\nNotably, the provided traceback is about a note.\n\nI don't think we should strive to match the behavior of GNU readelf or llvm-readelf when it comes to those nonfatal parse errors. That's not the purpose of readelf.py.\n@bakeromso\n\n> are you interested in further investigating these crashes? \n\nYes.\n\n> If so, how can I best provide them to you in a way that you find convenient?\n\nLet's start by providing one faulty binary, as an attachment to a comment on this very issue, zipped up (as GitHub won't let you provide a raw binary). I'll see where it takes us.\n@bakeromso \n\nIs this still an issue?\n@sevaa yes it is but I've not yet come around to recreating the test setup\n@sevaa sorry about the delay. Here is a zip with the ELFs that give a crash with pyelftools, but no crash with llvm-readelf.\n\nI get the crash by running `readelf.py -h [name of elf file].elf`\n\n[crashes.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/22929255/crashes.zip)\n### col_12to35_line35to35_ValueError.elf\nBogus stringtable section offset; pyelftools tries to retrieve its header eagerly and crashes. Lazy retrieval logic is already in place, this can be fixed trivially. **Modulo that**, the `e_version` in the ELF header is bogus (0xFFFFFFF) and is not in the enum - again, trivial fix - check if the value is in the enum before looking up.\n\n### col_15to32_line30to30_KeyError.elf\nBogus `EI_VERSION` in the header, one not in the enum - fix along the same lines.\n\n### col_17to34_line44to44_AttributeError.elf\nType ET_DYN, but no section called .dynamic. Trivial fix - check before dump. \n\n### col_20to37_line55to55_KeyError.elf\nBogus `e_version` again.\n\nIn conclusion, the mismatches *in header dump* can be addressed fairly easily, but other than satisfying one's obsession with matching llvm-readelf bug tolerance for bug tolerance, I don't see a ton of value there. Maybe some degree of vague future proofing, were those enums to legitimately become extended (which is quite unlikely). Also some limited value to those among us who study corrupt files for fun and/or living.\n\nNote that readelf dumps more involved than -h (dump file header) don't work in GNU readelf either; on as much as -S (section header dump) on 3 out of 4 files GNU readelf claims the file has no sections. I suspect the section header table is damaged on all of them but the only damage that pyelftools would surface is the corrupt stringtable.\nThank you for the follow up. Feel free to close the issue if this isn't worth the effort of fixing like you said, I understand.\n@eliben\n\nIt's a small set of fixes that will impose no performance penalty on the library proper. What do you think?\n> [@eliben](https://github.com/eliben)\n> \n> It's a small set of fixes that will impose no performance penalty on the library proper. What do you think?\n\nIf it's pretty minimal - just like a few safety checks here and there, I'm OK with merging it. Happy to take a look at a PR for specifics\n\nThanks!\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/eliben/pyelftools/commit/a200d556940f56c68b9f7397807532d0f0f50e02", "https://github.com/eliben/pyelftools/commit/8bb579672dcdf7c8f4c55356f92a9bb6e8cf7220", "https://github.com/eliben/pyelftools/commit/cc2e9a8816bd8165ab28f58556e367ccc92b6eb3"], "created_at": "2025-10-28T15:10:31Z"}
{"repo": "eliben/pyelftools", "pull_number": 625, "instance_id": "eliben__pyelftools-625", "issue_numbers": [623], "base_commit": "ecbd17e7bb2950aa97040ce3ee4fac15453d1a28", "patch": "diff --git a/elftools/dwarf/compileunit.py b/elftools/dwarf/compileunit.py\nindex 1e49b2ea..392400a4 100644\n--- a/elftools/dwarf/compileunit.py\n+++ b/elftools/dwarf/compileunit.py\n@@ -133,7 +133,42 @@ def iter_DIEs(self):\n         \"\"\" Iterate over all the DIEs in the CU, in order of their appearance.\n             Note that null DIEs will also be returned.\n         \"\"\"\n-        return self._iter_DIE_subtree(self.get_top_DIE())\n+        stm = self.dwarfinfo.debug_info_sec.stream\n+        pos = self.cu_die_offset\n+        end_pos = self.cu_offset + self.size\n+\n+        die = self.get_top_DIE()\n+        yield die\n+        pos += die.size\n+        parent = die\n+        i = 1\n+        while pos < end_pos:\n+            if i < len(self._diemap) and self._diemap[i] == pos: # DIE already cached\n+                die = self._dielist[i]\n+            else:\n+                die = DIE(self, stm, pos)\n+                self._dielist.insert(i, die)\n+                self._diemap.insert(i, pos)\n+            i += 1\n+\n+            die._parent = parent\n+\n+            if die.tag is None:\n+                parent._terminator = die\n+                parent = parent._parent\n+\n+            if die.has_children:\n+                parent = die\n+\n+            if die.tag == 'DW_TAG_imported_unit' and self.dwarfinfo.supplementary_dwarfinfo:\n+                # Falls back to subtree traversal in the supplemental DWARF. Any way to streamline that too?\n+                supp_die = die.get_DIE_from_attribute('DW_AT_import')\n+                yield from supp_die.cu._iter_DIE_subtree(supp_die)\n+            else:\n+                yield die\n+\n+            pos += die.size\n+\n \n     def iter_DIE_children(self, die):\n         \"\"\" Given a DIE, yields either its children, without null DIE list\n", "test_patch": "diff --git a/test/test_tree.py b/test/test_tree.py\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 00000000..1b691847\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/test/test_tree.py\n@@ -0,0 +1,55 @@\n+#------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n+# elftools tests\n+#\n+# Seva Alekseyev (sevaa@sprynet.com)\n+# This code is in the public domain\n+#\n+# Making sure the two ways of iterating through DIEs (linear and by tree)\n+# return an identically built tree (parents, children, terminators).\n+# \n+# TODO: find a siblingless file. None in the corpus so far.\n+#------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n+\n+import unittest\n+import os\n+from elftools.elf.elffile import ELFFile\n+\n+class TestTree(unittest.TestCase):\n+    def test_tree(self):\n+        self.run_test_on('dwarf_llpair.elf', 0, True)\n+        self.run_test_on('test_debugsup1.debug', 2, False)\n+\n+    def run_test_on(self, file_name, cu_index, test_cached):\n+        def die_summary(die):\n+            return (die.offset, die.tag, die._terminator.offset if die._terminator else None, die.get_parent().offset if die.get_parent() else None)\n+        \n+        with ELFFile.load_from_path(os.path.join('test', 'testfiles_for_unittests', file_name)) as elf:\n+            di = elf.get_dwarf_info()\n+            cu = next(c for i,c in enumerate(di.iter_CUs()) if i == cu_index)\n+            #_terminator is only set on a DIE *after* that DIE is yielded during enumeration\n+            DIEs = [d for d in cu.iter_DIEs()]\n+            seq_DIEs = [die_summary(d) for d in DIEs]\n+\n+            if test_cached:\n+                sample_offset = DIEs[len(DIEs) // 2].offset\n+                # Offset of a random DIE from the middle for later\n+\n+            # Deliberately erase the CU/DIE cache to force a repeat parse - this time using an explicit tree traversal\n+            di = elf.get_dwarf_info()\n+            cu = next(c for i,c in enumerate(di.iter_CUs()) if i == cu_index)\n+            DIEs = [d for d in cu._iter_DIE_subtree(cu.get_top_DIE())]\n+\n+            tree_DIEs = [die_summary(d) for d in DIEs]\n+            self.assertSequenceEqual(seq_DIEs, tree_DIEs)\n+\n+            if test_cached:\n+                # Another repeat parse, with a nonblank cache\n+                di = elf.get_dwarf_info()\n+                cu = next(c for i,c in enumerate(di.iter_CUs()) if i == cu_index)\n+                cu.get_DIE_from_refaddr(sample_offset) # Cache this random DIE in the middle\n+                DIEs = [d for d in cu.iter_DIEs()]\n+                seq_DIEs_x = [die_summary(d) for d in DIEs]\n+                self.assertSequenceEqual(seq_DIEs, seq_DIEs_x)\n+\n+if __name__ == '__main__':\n+    unittest.main()\n", "problem_statement": "function iter_DIEs  is verify slow\uff0c 1200000 dies takes 45 seconds\nfunction iter_DIEs  is very slow\uff0c 1200000 dies taking 45 seconds\uff0c I want to have multiple threads to process one cu per thread \uff0cbut the thread will report an error in iter_DIES, or is there any other way to speed up the traversal\uff0cI want to traversal all dies in 3 seconds\n", "hints_text": "![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/47b416bf-45b6-48a7-a3d1-44c4d614cd8e)\nYou are probably better off using a different library instead of pyelftools.\n> You are probably better off using a different library instead of pyelftools.\n\nIf pyelftools is used, is there a way to speed it up? For example, when iter_DIES, only the die with tag DW_TAG_Subprogram is traversed\nBased on my past profiling experience, I don't think you can make it so that the DIE traversal (using pyelftools) completes within three seconds. There is definitely room for improvement though.\nMay I see the thread initiation code? Not as a screenshot, as text.\n\nThat said, using a non-Python DWARF parser is solid advice. :)\n\nEDIT: now that I think of it, the underlying stream (shared by all CUs' iterators) would be the source of errors. Can be solved. @eliben this goes back to what we sort of discussed, how we are losing performance by treating DWARF sections as streams instead of memory buffers that they are. Construct and its streamy design is holding us back.\n> May I see the thread initiation code? Not as a screenshot, as text.\n> \n> That said, using a non-Python DWARF parser is solid advice. :)\n> \n> EDIT: now that I think of it, the underlying stream (shared by all CUs' iterators) would be the source of errors. Can be solved. [@eliben](https://github.com/eliben) this goes back to what we sort of discussed, how we are losing performance by treating DWARF sections as streams instead of memory buffers that they are. Construct and its streamy design is holding us back.\n\ndef process_cu(cu) :\n    for die in cu.iter_DIEs():\n         pass\ndef parallel_dwarf_parse(file_path):\n    with open(file_path, 'rb') as f:\n        thread = []\n        elffile = ELFFile(f)\n        if not elffile.has_dwarf_info():\n            return\n        dwarfInfo = elffile.get_dwarf_info()\n        for cu in dwarfInfo.iter_CUs():\n           th = threading.Thread(target=process_cu, args=(cu,))\n           th.start()\n           thread.append(th)\n        [t.join() for t in thread]\n        return\n\nerror info:\n![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/cf600132-9ea0-448d-b585-ba57eb4a5315)\n\nIf I want to use elftools, is there any way to speed up parsing\nYeah, I have repro. Thanks. OBTW, are you using the free threaded mode of Python 2.13? For a memory-only operation such as DIE parsing, I feel you could get quite a bit of performance from the free threaded mode, *once* pyelftools is ready for that. Also, since there is overhead to threading support, I'd prefer to not use it by default, and use the no-GIL flag (`sys._is_gil_enabled()`) as a trigger.\n\n@eliben: I could provide a fix that would allow for this kind of CU-driven parallelism. One caveat though. My idea is to construct multiple lightweight streams around the info section buffer for parallel access. Right now, *we don't store the info section buffer*. We store a `BytesIO` built around it. `BytesIO` is a blackbox. I have no idea whether/when does it copy the underlying buffer. Storing both the `BytesIO` and the buffer runs the risk of consuming twice the memory. I could replace the `BytesIO` with a lightweight read-only stream class (I have one already) that I know for a fact doesn't duplicate, but that *may* break things for library users out there - in a contrived scenario where they get the stream from a pyelftools' objects and work with it *assuming it was a BytesIO*. Unlikely, but who knows. Is that a risk we'd be willing to take?\n\nOBTW, I could also provide a fix as a sample as opposed to a PR - just for this case. It will be an ugly monkeypatch.\n@sevaa it's worth trying an experiment if you have the time. It'd be interesting to look at a PR to see how the code is affected (in terms of API change), as well as the performance effects\n> Yeah, I have repro. Thanks. OBTW, are you using the free threaded mode of Python 2.13? For a memory-only operation such as DIE parsing, I feel you could get quite a bit of performance from the free threaded mode, _once_ pyelftools is ready for that. Also, since there is overhead to threading support, I'd prefer to not use it by default, and use the no-GIL flag (`sys._is_gil_enabled()`) as a trigger.\n> \n> [@eliben](https://github.com/eliben): I could provide a fix that would allow for this kind of CU-driven parallelism. One caveat though. My idea is to construct multiple lightweight streams around the info section buffer for parallel access. Right now, _we don't store the info section buffer_. We store a `BytesIO` built around it. `BytesIO` is a blackbox. I have no idea whether/when does it copy the underlying buffer. Storing both the `BytesIO` and the buffer runs the risk of consuming twice the memory. I could replace the `BytesIO` with a lightweight read-only stream class (I have one already) that I know for a fact doesn't duplicate, but that _may_ break things for library users out there - in a contrived scenario where they get the stream from a pyelftools' objects and work with it _assuming it was a BytesIO_. Unlikely, but who knows. Is that a risk we'd be willing to take?\n> \n> OBTW, I could also provide a fix as a sample as opposed to a PR - just for this case. It will be an ugly monkeypatch.\n\nI am using Python 3.8, completely default behavior, without specifically setting the free threaded mode . Pyelftools may not be as fast as C language libraries such as libdw, but if it can support multi-threading, large binary parsing can really be much faster\nI can 99% promise that you **won't** get any performance enhancement from using threads under Python 3.8. Python notoriously has a GIL, global interpreter lock. When Python code executes on a thread (as opposed to, e. g., waiting for I/O), all other threads are stalled. There is no I/O in the DIE parsing logic - it's a completely in memory operation.\n> I can 99% promise that you **won't** get any performance enhancement from using threads under Python 3.8. Python notoriously has a GIL, global interpreter lock. When Python code executes on a thread (as opposed to, e. g., waiting for I/O), all other threads are stalled. There is no I/O in the DIE parsing logic - it's a completely in memory operation.\n\nthanks\uff0c if pyelftools support muti-threading, I can update python version\nFunny thing, with threads (even with handful of them) I'm getting weird overlarge memory consumption - up to 20GB in peak. The file I'm testing on consumes about 2 GB in single threaded mode (it's big). I'm getting MemoryErrors on threads and the process crashes.\n\nA part of the blame is on pyelftools - it caches aggressively (see #586), but still. 2 GB is due to the caches, but 20 is crazy. It reproduces consistently.\n\nI guess the experimental free threaded mode is not all it's cracked up to be. Sorry, I've tried. As a side note, running the single threaded DIE scan under the free threaded Python *increases* the run time by ~30%. Such is the overhead of basic thread sync in Python internals alone.\n\nI feel there is still some performance to be squeezed out of single threaded DIE parsing performance, but we'd be lucky if we got a two-fold improvement.\n@sevaa This issue might be causing the memory usage behavior you saw: https://github.com/python/cpython/issues/133136\nHi @sevaa, could you test with the latest Python 3.14 release (currently rc1)? It includes a fix for the issue Itfish linked to above.  The fix is backported to 3.13 as well but the 3.13.x release containing that fix is not out yet.  If you can make an example test case, I would try running it myself.\n\n\nI'd rather hold on until the proper 3.14 release.\n\nUnrelated, I've noticed that `CompileUnit.iter_DIEs()` is unnecessarily convoluted in terms of parse logic. Its purpose it to return the DIEs in the sequential order, but instead it relies on the logic of `CompileUnit.iter_DIE_children()`, which contains the **more complicated** logic of going over **immediate** children of a DIE. Especially on a siblingless DIE tree, this will contain extra work of parsing the whole subtree only to throw away the children of children.\n\nPhysically, DIEs are stored linearly. Logically, they are a tree. `iter_DIEs()` is expected to return a flat collection, but it does so by building a tree (out of a flat collection) and then flattening it. I feel this could be streamlined.\n\nThe downside would be that the logic of setting parents during parsing (normally done by `iter_DIE_children()`) would be somewhat duplicated. Since #611 seems to be stalled, I'll try to do some tests, and if we win any time, a PR.\n\nUPDATE: at a first stab, I've got about 7% performance increase for a firehose CU/DIE scan. @eliben - worth it or not?\n> UPDATE: at a first stab, I've got about 7% performance increase for a firehose CU/DIE scan. @eliben - worth it or not?\n\nSounds promising. Let's start a separate issue about it, or just a PR? We can then discuss this specific optimization without all the other baggage\n\n", "all_hints_text": "![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/47b416bf-45b6-48a7-a3d1-44c4d614cd8e)\nYou are probably better off using a different library instead of pyelftools.\n> You are probably better off using a different library instead of pyelftools.\n\nIf pyelftools is used, is there a way to speed it up? For example, when iter_DIES, only the die with tag DW_TAG_Subprogram is traversed\nBased on my past profiling experience, I don't think you can make it so that the DIE traversal (using pyelftools) completes within three seconds. There is definitely room for improvement though.\nMay I see the thread initiation code? Not as a screenshot, as text.\n\nThat said, using a non-Python DWARF parser is solid advice. :)\n\nEDIT: now that I think of it, the underlying stream (shared by all CUs' iterators) would be the source of errors. Can be solved. @eliben this goes back to what we sort of discussed, how we are losing performance by treating DWARF sections as streams instead of memory buffers that they are. Construct and its streamy design is holding us back.\n> May I see the thread initiation code? Not as a screenshot, as text.\n> \n> That said, using a non-Python DWARF parser is solid advice. :)\n> \n> EDIT: now that I think of it, the underlying stream (shared by all CUs' iterators) would be the source of errors. Can be solved. [@eliben](https://github.com/eliben) this goes back to what we sort of discussed, how we are losing performance by treating DWARF sections as streams instead of memory buffers that they are. Construct and its streamy design is holding us back.\n\ndef process_cu(cu) :\n    for die in cu.iter_DIEs():\n         pass\ndef parallel_dwarf_parse(file_path):\n    with open(file_path, 'rb') as f:\n        thread = []\n        elffile = ELFFile(f)\n        if not elffile.has_dwarf_info():\n            return\n        dwarfInfo = elffile.get_dwarf_info()\n        for cu in dwarfInfo.iter_CUs():\n           th = threading.Thread(target=process_cu, args=(cu,))\n           th.start()\n           thread.append(th)\n        [t.join() for t in thread]\n        return\n\nerror info:\n![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/cf600132-9ea0-448d-b585-ba57eb4a5315)\n\nIf I want to use elftools, is there any way to speed up parsing\nYeah, I have repro. Thanks. OBTW, are you using the free threaded mode of Python 2.13? For a memory-only operation such as DIE parsing, I feel you could get quite a bit of performance from the free threaded mode, *once* pyelftools is ready for that. Also, since there is overhead to threading support, I'd prefer to not use it by default, and use the no-GIL flag (`sys._is_gil_enabled()`) as a trigger.\n\n@eliben: I could provide a fix that would allow for this kind of CU-driven parallelism. One caveat though. My idea is to construct multiple lightweight streams around the info section buffer for parallel access. Right now, *we don't store the info section buffer*. We store a `BytesIO` built around it. `BytesIO` is a blackbox. I have no idea whether/when does it copy the underlying buffer. Storing both the `BytesIO` and the buffer runs the risk of consuming twice the memory. I could replace the `BytesIO` with a lightweight read-only stream class (I have one already) that I know for a fact doesn't duplicate, but that *may* break things for library users out there - in a contrived scenario where they get the stream from a pyelftools' objects and work with it *assuming it was a BytesIO*. Unlikely, but who knows. Is that a risk we'd be willing to take?\n\nOBTW, I could also provide a fix as a sample as opposed to a PR - just for this case. It will be an ugly monkeypatch.\n@sevaa it's worth trying an experiment if you have the time. It'd be interesting to look at a PR to see how the code is affected (in terms of API change), as well as the performance effects\n> Yeah, I have repro. Thanks. OBTW, are you using the free threaded mode of Python 2.13? For a memory-only operation such as DIE parsing, I feel you could get quite a bit of performance from the free threaded mode, _once_ pyelftools is ready for that. Also, since there is overhead to threading support, I'd prefer to not use it by default, and use the no-GIL flag (`sys._is_gil_enabled()`) as a trigger.\n> \n> [@eliben](https://github.com/eliben): I could provide a fix that would allow for this kind of CU-driven parallelism. One caveat though. My idea is to construct multiple lightweight streams around the info section buffer for parallel access. Right now, _we don't store the info section buffer_. We store a `BytesIO` built around it. `BytesIO` is a blackbox. I have no idea whether/when does it copy the underlying buffer. Storing both the `BytesIO` and the buffer runs the risk of consuming twice the memory. I could replace the `BytesIO` with a lightweight read-only stream class (I have one already) that I know for a fact doesn't duplicate, but that _may_ break things for library users out there - in a contrived scenario where they get the stream from a pyelftools' objects and work with it _assuming it was a BytesIO_. Unlikely, but who knows. Is that a risk we'd be willing to take?\n> \n> OBTW, I could also provide a fix as a sample as opposed to a PR - just for this case. It will be an ugly monkeypatch.\n\nI am using Python 3.8, completely default behavior, without specifically setting the free threaded mode . Pyelftools may not be as fast as C language libraries such as libdw, but if it can support multi-threading, large binary parsing can really be much faster\nI can 99% promise that you **won't** get any performance enhancement from using threads under Python 3.8. Python notoriously has a GIL, global interpreter lock. When Python code executes on a thread (as opposed to, e. g., waiting for I/O), all other threads are stalled. There is no I/O in the DIE parsing logic - it's a completely in memory operation.\n> I can 99% promise that you **won't** get any performance enhancement from using threads under Python 3.8. Python notoriously has a GIL, global interpreter lock. When Python code executes on a thread (as opposed to, e. g., waiting for I/O), all other threads are stalled. There is no I/O in the DIE parsing logic - it's a completely in memory operation.\n\nthanks\uff0c if pyelftools support muti-threading, I can update python version\nFunny thing, with threads (even with handful of them) I'm getting weird overlarge memory consumption - up to 20GB in peak. The file I'm testing on consumes about 2 GB in single threaded mode (it's big). I'm getting MemoryErrors on threads and the process crashes.\n\nA part of the blame is on pyelftools - it caches aggressively (see #586), but still. 2 GB is due to the caches, but 20 is crazy. It reproduces consistently.\n\nI guess the experimental free threaded mode is not all it's cracked up to be. Sorry, I've tried. As a side note, running the single threaded DIE scan under the free threaded Python *increases* the run time by ~30%. Such is the overhead of basic thread sync in Python internals alone.\n\nI feel there is still some performance to be squeezed out of single threaded DIE parsing performance, but we'd be lucky if we got a two-fold improvement.\n@sevaa This issue might be causing the memory usage behavior you saw: https://github.com/python/cpython/issues/133136\nHi @sevaa, could you test with the latest Python 3.14 release (currently rc1)? It includes a fix for the issue Itfish linked to above.  The fix is backported to 3.13 as well but the 3.13.x release containing that fix is not out yet.  If you can make an example test case, I would try running it myself.\n\n\nI'd rather hold on until the proper 3.14 release.\n\nUnrelated, I've noticed that `CompileUnit.iter_DIEs()` is unnecessarily convoluted in terms of parse logic. Its purpose it to return the DIEs in the sequential order, but instead it relies on the logic of `CompileUnit.iter_DIE_children()`, which contains the **more complicated** logic of going over **immediate** children of a DIE. Especially on a siblingless DIE tree, this will contain extra work of parsing the whole subtree only to throw away the children of children.\n\nPhysically, DIEs are stored linearly. Logically, they are a tree. `iter_DIEs()` is expected to return a flat collection, but it does so by building a tree (out of a flat collection) and then flattening it. I feel this could be streamlined.\n\nThe downside would be that the logic of setting parents during parsing (normally done by `iter_DIE_children()`) would be somewhat duplicated. Since #611 seems to be stalled, I'll try to do some tests, and if we win any time, a PR.\n\nUPDATE: at a first stab, I've got about 7% performance increase for a firehose CU/DIE scan. @eliben - worth it or not?\n> UPDATE: at a first stab, I've got about 7% performance increase for a firehose CU/DIE scan. @eliben - worth it or not?\n\nSounds promising. Let's start a separate issue about it, or just a PR? We can then discuss this specific optimization without all the other baggage\nFYI, here is a superfast DIE scan function:\n\n```\ndef iter_DIEs_really_fast(cu):\n        stm = cu.dwarfinfo.debug_info_sec.stream\n        pos = cu.cu_die_offset\n        end_pos = cu.cu_offset + self.size\n        while pos < end_pos:\n            die = DIE(cu, stm, pos)\n            yield die\n            pos += die.size\n```\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/eliben/pyelftools/commit/eb949d3125f45d0de598e12b6518e6219270595a", "https://github.com/eliben/pyelftools/commit/74a0d17a2cdc22ecb8c60d0cc39d6376f4af77fd"], "created_at": "2025-08-30T01:02:39Z"}
{"repo": "eliben/pyelftools", "pull_number": 630, "instance_id": "eliben__pyelftools-630", "issue_numbers": [629], "base_commit": "9e6f7295cbbc3a91d09d5cd37c337a044612d597", "patch": "diff --git a/elftools/dwarf/structs.py b/elftools/dwarf/structs.py\nindex 02e88573..1212fc3b 100644\n--- a/elftools/dwarf/structs.py\n+++ b/elftools/dwarf/structs.py\n@@ -299,6 +299,7 @@ def _create_dw_form(self):\n             DW_FORM_strp=self.the_Dwarf_offset,\n             DW_FORM_strp_sup=self.the_Dwarf_offset,\n             DW_FORM_line_strp=self.the_Dwarf_offset,\n+            DW_FORM_strx=self.the_Dwarf_uleb128,\n             DW_FORM_strx1=self.the_Dwarf_uint8,\n             DW_FORM_strx2=self.the_Dwarf_uint16,\n             DW_FORM_strx3=self.Dwarf_uint24(''),\n@@ -317,7 +318,7 @@ def _create_dw_form(self):\n \n             DW_FORM_indirect=self.the_Dwarf_uleb128,\n \n-            # Treated separatedly while parsing, but here so that all forms resovle\n+            # Treated separatedly while parsing, but here so that all forms resolve\n             DW_FORM_implicit_const=None,\n \n             # New forms in DWARFv4\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "KeyError: `DW_FORM_strx` crash for DWARF5\nI'm seeing this crash in 0.32 when attempting to read a DWARF v5 file produced by Xcode26:\n```\n        top_DIE = CU.get_top_DIE()\n      File \"/python3.13/site-packages/elft\n    ools/dwarf/compileunit.py\", line 92, in get_top_DIE\n        top = DIE(\n                cu=self,\n                stream=self.dwarfinfo.debug_info_sec.stream,\n                offset=self.cu_die_offset)\n      File \"/python3.13/site-packages/elft\n    ools/dwarf/die.py\", line 99, in __init__\n        self._parse_DIE()\n        ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~^^\n      File \"/python3.13/site-packages/elft\n    ools/dwarf/die.py\", line 264, in _parse_DIE\n        raw_value = structs.Dwarf_dw_form[form].parse_stream(stream)\n                    ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~^^^^^^\n    KeyError: 'DW_FORM_strx'\n```\n\nIs DWARF v5 only partially supported right now?\n", "hints_text": "In `structs.py` looks like these are currently added:\n\n```\n            DW_FORM_strx1=self.the_Dwarf_uint8,\n            DW_FORM_strx2=self.the_Dwarf_uint16,\n            DW_FORM_strx3=self.Dwarf_uint24(''),\n            DW_FORM_strx4=self.Dwarf_uint64(''),\n```\n\nfrom what I can tell in the spec this should be `The representation of a DW_FORM_strx value is an unsigned LEB128 value`\nLooks like we missed it at the time. Sorry, will address. Elsewhere where indirect string forms are listed (translating offsets to strings), `strx` is present.\n\n", "all_hints_text": "In `structs.py` looks like these are currently added:\n\n```\n            DW_FORM_strx1=self.the_Dwarf_uint8,\n            DW_FORM_strx2=self.the_Dwarf_uint16,\n            DW_FORM_strx3=self.Dwarf_uint24(''),\n            DW_FORM_strx4=self.Dwarf_uint64(''),\n```\n\nfrom what I can tell in the spec this should be `The representation of a DW_FORM_strx value is an unsigned LEB128 value`\nLooks like we missed it at the time. Sorry, will address. Elsewhere where indirect string forms are listed (translating offsets to strings), `strx` is present.\nFor a monkeypatch, run the following early on in the project:\n\n```\ndef monkeypatch():\n    import elftools.dwarf.dwarfinfo\n    old_create_structs = elftools.dwarf.dwarfinfo.DWARFStructs._create_structs\n    def _create_structs(self):\n        old_create_structs(self)\n        self.Dwarf_dw_form['DW_FORM_strx'] = self.the_Dwarf_uleb128\n    elftools.dwarf.dwarfinfo.DWARFStructs._create_structs = _create_structs\n```\n\nThanks, the monkeypatch worked great.\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/eliben/pyelftools/commit/1f7b90ffe6555bd9bbcb47103b753c94e1d9a85f"], "created_at": "2025-11-15T14:26:15Z"}
